Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}(trimmed and thinly sliced), separating whites from greens. Peel and grate or mince @ginger{1%thumb}(peeled and grated). Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}(minced). Quarter @lime{1}(quartered).

Melt @butter{1%tablespoon} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites and half the ginger; cook until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Add @jasmine rice{3/4%cup}, 1 1/4 cups @water{1 1/4%cups} (2 1/4 cups for 4 servings), and a big pinch of @salt{pinch} to same pot. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} and pat dry with paper towels. Toss in a #medium bowl{} with garlic, half the @hoisin sauce{2%tablespoon} (all the hoisin for 4 servings), and remaining ginger. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Set aside to marinate for at least ~{5%minutes}.

Meanwhile, toss @green beans{6%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} and a pinch of salt and pepper. Roast, tossing halfway through, until browned and slightly crisp, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Heat a drizzle of remaining oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add shrimp mixture and cook, stirring, until shrimp is opaque and cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}. Divide rice between plates; top with green beans and shrimp. Sprinkle with scallion greens and as many @sesame seeds{1%tablespoon} as you like. Serve with lime wedges on the side.

> If you're like us, you've seen a lot of stir-fries in your day. But thanks to our sweet hoisin shrimp marinade, aromatic rice, and a sprinkle of nutty sesame seeds, this one is bound to top them all. It cooks super-quickly and brings a tour de force of Asian-style flavors that even the pickiest of eaters will love.